  <item>
    <title>*Dark Emacs windows* in GNOME</title>
    <link>http://nicolas-petton.fr/blog/emacs-dark-window-decoration.html#sec-1</link>
    <author>Nicolas Petton</author>
    <guid isPermaLink="false">http://nicolas-petton.fr/blog/emacs-dark-window-decoration.html#sec-1</guid>
    <pubDate>Fri, 29 Aug 2014 09:25:00 +0200</pubDate>

    <description><![CDATA[
    <p>
    Gnome 3&rsquo;s default theme Adwaita has support for both light and dark
    window decorations. Many media apps like Totem use the dark theme. It
    puts the focus on the content and it&rsquo;s easier on the eyes.
    </p>

    <p>
    Emacs with a <a href="https://github.com/niflheim-theme/emacs">dark theme</a> and the large white-ish window decoration
    isn&rsquo;t really a fit on my desktop, but that can be easily fixed using a
    bit of elisp with xprop!
    </p>

    <div class="org-src-container">

    <pre class="src src-emacs-lisp">(<span style="color: #f7af75; font-weight: bold;">defun</span> <span style="color: #cbaaf5;">set-selected-frame-dark</span> ()
    (interactive)
    (<span style="color: #f7af75; font-weight: bold;">let</span> ((frame-name (get-frame-name (selected-frame))))
    (call-process-shell-command (concat <span style="color: #789771;">"xprop -f _GTK_THEME_VARIANT 8u -set _GTK_THEME_VARIANT \"dark\" -name \""</span>
    frame-name
    <span style="color: #789771;">"\""</span>))))

    (<span style="color: #f7af75; font-weight: bold;">if</span> (window-system)
    (set-selected-frame-dark))
    </pre>
    </div>

    <p>
    Here&rsquo;s a screenshot of both versions:
    </p>

    <p>
    <img src="http://nicolas-petton.fr/blog/../images/emacs-light.png" alt="emacs-light.png" />
    <img src="http://nicolas-petton.fr/blog/../images/emacs-dark.png" alt="emacs-dark.png" />
    </p>


